    <insight>
        <p>
            From the activity, we can see that the measurements of the length of the textbook can be slightly longer or shorter than the working length.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Limit of measurement}\; = \amp \; \frac{\text{smallest unit}}{2} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Upper limit}\; = \amp \; \text{working value}\; + \;\text{limit of measurement} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Lower limit}\; = \amp \; \text{working value}\; - \;\text{limit of measurement} </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            The limits of measurement are the maximum and minimum values that a measurement can take. The upper limit is the actual value plus the limit of measurement, while the lower limit is the actual value minus the limit of measurement.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Lower limit}\; \le \amp \; \text{working value}\; \le \text{Upper limit} </mrow>
            </md>
            
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the limits within which the measurements below lie:
                </p> 
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <m>26 </m> cm
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>26.0 </m> cm
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>26.07 </m> cm
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The measurement <m>26 </m> cm has no decimal places.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The error is <m>0.5 </m> cm, so the limits are:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>25.5 </m> cm and <m>26.5 </m> cm
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The measurement <m>26.0 </m> cm has one decimal place.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The error is <m>0.05 </m> cm, so the limits are:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>25.95 </m> cm and <m>26.05 </m> cm
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The measurement <m>26.07 </m> cm has two decimal places.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The error is <m>0.005 </m> cm, so the limits are:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>26.065 </m> cm and <m>26.075 </m> cm
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A length is measured as <m>15.2 </m> cm. Find the limits within which the measurement lies.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The measurement <m>15.2 </m> cm has one decimal place.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The error is <m>0.05 </m> cm, so the limits are:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>15.15 </m> cm and <m>15.25 </m> cm
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The best time for <m>100 </m> m dash on a schol sports day is <m>10.7 </m> seconds. Find the limits within which the actual time lies.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The measurement <m>10.7 </m> seconds has one decimal place.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The error is <m>0.05 </m> seconds, so the limits are:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>10.65 </m> seconds and <m>10.75 </m> seconds
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

